recordings.rmk: Bird was concealed in thick roadside shrubs in an area which had received good amounts of rain in the weeks leading up to March. It remained concealed most of the time but was calling from a single perch in the depths of said shrubs. It would occasionally break song to shift its position slightly, hopping to another nearby branch from which it would then resume calling. It did this for roughly thirty minutes before going quiet for the rest of the day.

It sounds very much like a Common Grasshopper warbler, but the sound is not as monotonous as it usually is. The sound is reminiscent of Savi's warbler and has characteristics a little bit like River warbler, but neither is identical to this recording. When studied closely, the song is made up of two or three syllables separated by distinct pauses, and these pauses are absent in its normal song. Locustella naevia straminea is reasonably similar. Another recording of the same bird can be found in XC240730. This and a number of other unusual sounding Locustellas have been collected into the Recording set [Unusual River warbler (Locustella fluviatilis) songs](http://www.xeno-canto.org/set/2058)

The recording was normalized.It consists of three repetitions each with a duration of 10, 4 and 15 seconds. The last one was unfortunately terminated before it actually ended. 

Each repetition is composed of two parts. The first part (1 second) consists of repetitive sound units with a frequency of 1300 units per minute. The song then slows down to a frequency of the sound units is 600 per minute. The characteristics of the units differ between the parts.
